Secretary General Ban Ki-moon says his response to Russia's military support for Syria is that "there is no military solution" to the conflict that lasts nearly five years and more weapons would only exacerbate the violence and suffering of millions of people.
The UN chief again called on all parties, including the divided UN Security Council to unite and support negotiations to find a political solution.
Ban said on Wednesday at a conference that he intends to meet this month with the foreign ministers of five permanent countries present at the Council - the United States, Russia, China, England and France - at the ministerial session of the General Assembly to discuss Syria.
Ban expressed regret that the divisions in the council and between the Syrian people and the regional authorities "did this situation unsolved".
Ban called on the five permanent members to demonstrate the solidarity and unity shown when they were able to conclude an agreement on Iran's nuclear weapons, thus addressing the crisis in Syria.
