On the occasion of the most awaited meetings in recent years, the responsible for the development of policies within the Federal Reserve will spend two days this week around a 27-foot Honduran mahon meal to decide whether the time has come to raise a key interest rate for the first time in almost a decade.
Above them, at the end of the headquarters meeting room, there will be a wall painting of the United States.
The map is meant to recall that Janet L. Yellen, President Fed, and his colleagues must put the economic interests of the nation above all else.
The Central Bank has received a double task from Congress: to maximize the employment rate in the US and to maintain price stability.
But since the great economic crisis, Fed leaders have confirmed that there is a third unwritten task: financial stability.
And this third task could be the factor X in a decision that is too difficult to anticipate, which will be announced on Tuesday, and which will determine whether the US economy is prepared to be dealt with by the unprecedented incentive offered by the short-term interest rate almost zero in effect from the end of 2008.
Even if most data indicate a strong growing economy, recent global financial market turmoil could scare Fed officials already cautious about adding volatility by increasing the reference rate to federal funds - even with only a quarter of a percentage point.
"Evidently, the labour market and inflation will be the first and main issues to follow," said Lindsey M. Piegza, chief economist at Stifel Nicolaus & Co. brokerage firm.
"But I think that if they were looking for an excuse not to raise the interest rate, growing uncertainty on the world market is enough to give them more arguments," she said.
There is no consensus as to the decision that Fed will take, which in itself provokes instability in the financial market.
About half of Bloomberg's recently questioned economists have anticipated an increase in interest rate this week.
But financial markets expect Fed to delay, a key indicator showing that the likelihood of growth is only 30%.
This would indicate a drop on the stock exchange if the Fed increases the interest rate, unless policy makers attenuate the impact by promising that it would pass a long time to the next increase.
Tuesday, industrial average Dow Jones climbed 228.89 points, or 1.4%, to 16,599.85.
The move was triggered by expectations that the Fed decision makers will keep the interest rate stable this week, said John Lonski, chief economist at Moody's Capital Markets Research Group.
"It would be surprising if Fed grew the interest rate at the moment," Lonski said.
If the Fed decision makers would do so, "they should take deep action in their policies to avoid panic on financial markets".
Other experts said that an increase in interest rate would calm financial markets because it would remove uncertainty about the timing of the Fed action.
Just a month ago, the Fed seemed to be about to increase the rate by 0.25% this month, the first small step towards slow tightening the monetary conditions that would confirm the strength of US recovery.
Yellen said in the spring and early summer that it expected an increase in the interest rate this year despite the high objections of liberals that more economic progress would be needed.
Although job creation slowed down in August, labour market growth was solid this year.
The unemployment rate fell to 5.1% last month, the lowest in more than seven years and close to the level considered by the Fed as total employment.
Wage gains have shown signs of growth.
And while inflation continued to fail to reach the annual target of the central bank, the Fed decision makers claimed that a key reason was the temporary effect of the sudden decline in oil prices.
The economy "can cope with higher rates and needs them, given the strain on the labour market," said Ian Shepherdson, chief economist at Pantheon Macroeconomics.
But global financial markets began to enter fibrillations at the end of this month, after China devalued its currency.
The Dow Jones industrial media has fallen by 16% below the record peak in May, as investors have feared that slowing the Chinese economy will bring down global growth.
The market has rebounded somewhat this month, the Dow index now being about 10% below the maximum of May.
For Fed decision makers, market turmoil is added to the complex calculation of the time of increase of the interest rate.
"Without what happened on the financial markets and the news about the weakening of the Chinese economy over the past few weeks, it would be more firm at the meeting," said Stephen D. Oliner, experienced researcher at UCLA Ziman Center for Real Estate and former official Fed.
Now, he expects that they will wait at least a month to manage the effects better.
"There is a lot of uncertainty about what will be the impact on the US economy, and they almost haven't given the basis for further events in China," Oliner said.
The welfare of the global economy is not one of the major interests of the Fed, so it should not be taken into account in making decisions.
In reality, however, the Fed has become a global monetary authority.
In recent years, the influence of the central bank has been enormous.
The simple allusion of the president since then, Ben S. Bernanke, in 2013, that the Fed could "enough" its monetary expansion triggered earthquakes on global markets.
In a world where markets and economies are increasingly engulfed, Fed officials are expected not only to monitor progress in other areas but also to consult with other central banks and experts to better interpret the world economy.
Its decision-making process is "more art than science," said Zachary Karabell, head of the global strategy department of the investment company Envestnet Inc.
Jeffrey Laker, President of the Federal Reserve Bank of Richmond, Va., said this month that "Fed has an oversized reaction to changes in the financial market that seem to be unrelated to economic bases."
As a member of the Federal Open Market Commission, the decision-making body, which supported the increase in interest rates, has, for example, offered the 1998-99 decisions.
A financial crisis that affected Asia caused the Fed to reduce the benchmark rate by 0.75% in three meetings, "despite the implications of limited identification for U.S. development," Lacker said.
A year later, Fed officials returned to the respective decreases.
Fed should only put the issue of financial stability first in the case of a major crisis, as was the 2008 market earthquake, said Adam S. Posen, former member of the Bank of England interest rate commission.
The last hectic period does not go even further at that level, he said.
"We certainly don't want to be in a position to fear an increase in interest rates because the markets are upset," Posen, President Peterson Institute for International Economics, said.
The Federal Reserve Act still holds the double mandate and does not mention financial stability and, until something changes in this regard, I do not think that it should take any early action.
