Operations for weight loss, called bariatric surgery, use various methods to reduce the stomach.
They reduce the feeling of hunger and limit the ability of the body to absorb food.
Over the years, bariatric surgery has proven effective in the treatment of type 2 diabetes, but most studies have been conducted in people with morbid obesity with a body mass index (BMI) 35 or higher.
BMI, a weight unit relative to height, is considered normal in the 18.5-24.9 range.
The BMI value of at least 25 indicates that one person is overweight and persons with BMI over 30 are considered obese.
You can calculate the BMI by accessing: 1.usa.gov/1D0ZqDv.
For the new study, researchers at the Min-Sheng General Hospital in Taiwan used the data collected after 2007 in a trial comparing two types of bariatric surgery - gastric bypass and mansoon gastrectomy - in the medical treatment of type 2 diabetes in people with mild obesity.
Mean BMI in those who underwent surgery decreased from 31 to 24.5 by the end of the fifth year in the study.
Meanwhile, BMI in people who received non-surgical treatment for diabetes has remained at nearly the same level, i.e. 29.
Of those who have undergone surgery, diabetes has healed completely at 36% and partially at 28%.
In the group treated by medical methods, by comparison, diabetes mellitus healed completely at only 1% and partially at only 2% of subjects.
In addition, the control of blood pressure, triglycerides and LDL cholesterol "bad" were generally better in the surgical group," the authors concluded.
Researchers have also monitored blood levels of A1c which reflect blood glucose levels over time.
Researchers write that the optimal level of A1c haemoglobin is below 7%.
After surgery, the mean level of A1c haemoglobin decreased from approximately 9% to approximately 6%.
But in the medically treated group, it remained at about 8%.
