The research team also compared the average results associated with the two types of surgery.
In the fifth year, compared to the mansoon gastrectomy group, the bypass surgery group lost more weight (18.7 compared to 14.2 kg), recorded a higher decrease in BMI (7.4 compared to 5.1) and haemoglobin A1c (3.1% compared to 2.1%) and had a higher probability of complete remission of diabetes (46.9% compared to 16.7%).
Although the new study does not indicate a benefit in survival or surgery after five years, there is evidence from a study carried out on large-weighted people in Sweden that surgical intervention prolongs life, Blackstone says, from Arizona University, Faculty of Medicine - Phoenix.
In the Swedish study, obese individuals who underwent bariatric surgery had a probability of approximately 29% less likely to die after 15 years, compared to a group who tried more conventional methods.
Although the new study did not indicate a benefit in survival in patients who have undergone surgery, Blackstone said it is an optimistic aspect for individuals with BMI below 35 procedural stakeholders.
"This is the point where this work is critical because it states that this surgery is safe in the lower BMI group," she says, without increasing the risk of death or kidney disease.
