FriendsFest: comedy series that taught us important lessons about friendship between men
The absence of similar characters in the series is evident, given the need for men to open up is now more desperate than ever, suicide rates among young men reaching the top of the last 15 years.
In 2013, suicide was the main cause of death in men 20-45 years of age in the UK, and remains three times more frequent in men than in women.
In an attempt to address the problem, Campaign Against Unhappy Life (Campaign Against Living Miserably (CALM)) designated 2015 as the Year of Man, wanting to question the culture that prevents men from seeking help when they need it.
Friendship is at the center of the struggle to succeed this challenge.
A recent study of more than 2000 high school students with symptoms of depression concluded that if the patient is surrounded by enough friends “with a healthy state of disposition”, his chances of recovery are doubled.
To the same extent, for people who are not depressed, a circle of healthy friends reduces the likelihood of mental disorders to half the probability of occurring.
Of course, in order for friendship to take effect, it must first be accessible.
In this era of communication dominated by social networks, where emphasis is placed on style rather than substance, the immediate nature of the response is often given priority before contact with meaning.
Our digital lives have doubled the need to create the appearance of a strong personality, open to fun and success, even if in reality isolation is the one that dominates.
This superficial success is dominated by what psychologists call extrinsic values; money, image, social status, all at the cost of intrinsic values - our inner desire for personal development and friendship - which affects our mental health even deeper.
The billionaire inventor of a video game recently explained that money doesn't really buy happiness.
The beauty of the Friends series was that it drew attention to this idea.
The characters were not defined by the job but by their personality, which they showed by interacting as friends.
The humour of Joey and Chandler's frequent hugs, the moments when they look at football in their comfortable shoes, and Ross' passion for Rachel came from the fact that men are known to be able to associate with this situation, even though they often fail to fully explore their feelings.
As one social worker explained to me: ..."my role in listening to people with a suicide tendency and depression showed how even the smallest interactions with friends can make the difference."
Often, people who appeal to us do not feel able to talk to friends.
The old saying to handle yourself is strong, as is the feeling of being perceived as a weak person if you speak openly about problems.
Friends is one of the series that come to mind when I try to offer more mechanisms for long-term psychological adaptation.
The series highlighted the small moments of friendship between men.
As much as it helps the objective, external intervention, through the phone, people reached in times of despair, long-term support comes from family and close friends.
Thus, if you attend this weekend at FriendsFest organized by Comedy Central, with the full play of the filming plates to celebrate the event, why not invite your friends to a coffee in Central Perk.
Or, even better, if you see someone alone in Starbucks, smile and say hello.
You never know what difference your friendship could make.
