The government approved, on Wednesday, "The National Strategy on Immigration for the period 2015-2018" and "The Action Plan for the current year", documents considered to be "still a stage in Romania's efforts to modernise the process of managing immigration in the national territory", according to a press release.
The above-mentioned source shows that the strategy aims to effectively manage the phenomenon of immigration, including general strategic objectives, specific objectives and action guidelines that reflect the policies set at European level, adapted to national realities.
In view of the problems facing the countries in the immediate vicinity of Romania, measures are envisaged for the united management and coherence of situations caused by the possible occurrence of an influx of illegal immigrants in Romania, generated by the political, social, economic or military crisis.
"Roman authorities will contribute to the creation of a flexible admission system, but at the same time they will pay special attention to citizens from countries with a potential migrationist or which may be detrimental to national security," the remembered source adds.
The strategy identifies a number of factors that can influence immigration and asylum, including maintaining the conflict situation in Syria, reactivating the conflict in Iraq, maintaining an unstable situation in neighbouring areas of Romania (Ukraine, Transnistria), perpetuating and increasing the Israeli-Palestinian armed conflict.
On the other hand, the document sets a number of general strategic objectives related to immigration, such as: promoting legal migration, more rigorous checks on the legality of the seat of third-country nationals on the territory of Romania and the proper application of removal measures and restrictive measures, the improvement of the national asylum system.
The national strategy shall also include specific objectives relevant to the transposition and implementation of the general strategic objectives.
These include: facilitating access to third-party citizens in Romania who respond to the needs of the labour force, promoting access to third-country citizens to higher learning institutions in Romania for the fields and professions identified as deficit.
Concerning the 2015 Action Plan, the Government considers that it represents "a means of establishing concrete activities leading to the creation of a flexible system for stopping the growing migration phenomenon".
Romania, in a European labour market top
Latvia, Romania and Bulgaria recorded a high increase in the total labour cost of the Member States of the European Union in the second quarter of the year compared to the similar period of 2014, according to data published on Wednesday by the European Statistical Office (Eurostat).
The index refers to employer staff expenses.
Thus, in the period April to June 2015, the total cost of the labour force rose by 1.9% in the European Union and by 1.6% in the euro area.
Romania, third place in the EU at rising labour cost
The highest growth rates were reported in Latvia (7.9%), Romania (7.7%), Bulgaria (6.8%), Estonia (5.5%) and Lithuania (4.3%).
The only EU states where the hourly cost of the labour force fell in the second quarter of this year were Greece (minus 2.9%), Cyprus (minus 1.2%) and Italy (minus 0.4%).
The increase in labour costs in Romania from April to June 2015 is mainly due to the increase in the hourly cost of the labour force in industry and services, with 7.9% and 7.6%, respectively.
In the construction sector, Romania recorded an advance of 5.8% of the hourly cost of the labour force.
